A great recipe and a fabulous gravy. You don't need so many shallots and I think there is too much butter in the gravy but it was delicious. I would like to have a good substitute cut instead of the tenderloin which ran me $100.

Rating: 4
Made this last night for birthday dinnner for 10 along with potato,cheese,chives and bell pepper crostini all from this site. All I can say is we ran out of gravy and nearly had a riot! The sauce was unbelievable and it was a crowd of gourmets judging. You cannot have enough sauce because folks will put it on EVERYTHING. I'd put it on ice cream! I used a Top loin vs. tenderloin and although I did not like the cut, others did. Recipe proportions and instructions were perfect (except broth) and easily modified up. We did not make gravy in roaster, but used a skillet - seemed easier and worked well. I used 8 - 14oz cans of broth; 6 were low sodium and 2 regular (yes I made a lot of sauce and still ran out). I think that was the right proportion of saltiness, any more and it would have been too much in my opinion. Used half ketchup and half tomato paste. Used both port and merlot. Added a tsp of demi-glaze. Did not add as much butter at end. Used a few less shallots, but don't skimp - they make the sauce. At end, sauce will continue to thicken so stop thickening just prior to desired thickness. We reduced sauce a lot at end step and ended up with about 6 cups gravy (wasn't enough!). Got meat and shallots at Costco so not too pricey. Meat time and temp were right on. Be careful not to overcook - it's easy to do. Suprised that as bloody as the meat drippings were, many pieces were well done, but fortunately not overdone. Clearly a keeper recipe!

