My family and regular guests for Christmas dinner insist that we serve this roast and "gravy" -- which I've done to rave reviews the past three years. I use a whole filet, cut in half, usually 6-61/2 pounds, which I cook to 130 degrees in slightly less than an hour for lovely medium rare beef. The sauce is easily made in advance, and works with and without the buerre manie finish. We usually have "cardio mashed potatoes" (using cream cheese and butter, also made in advance), and this year, a new green bean recipe (from this site) with ground cloves and lemon zest (delicious!). Salad with pears and roasted pecans rounds out our feast. I've cut down the sauce recipe by half, which works out well.

Rating: 3
I made this for Christmas dinner and it was a hit with all 13 guests! The tenderloin was about 6 1/2 lbs. and probably could of been a little bigger. There was one slice left but I think that if there had been more sitting on the platter it would of been eaten. I used the low sodium broth and didn't salt the tenderloin since it was seared in the bacon fat. I was afraid of it being too salty like the other reviewers had mentioned. The recipe does make alot of sauce. My family is a lover of onions and there was still plenty of shallots left over. You could certainly scale down the sauce. I served the tenderloin with two other great recipes from this site (both can be made the day before): Potatoes with Leeks and Gruyere & Warm Green Bean Salad with Pine Nuts and Basil. I used pecans instead of the pine nuts. We will definately be serving this again.

