I am making this for the fourth year in a row for Christmas dinner. It's delicious and not too hard for a rank amateur such as myself. One word of cauton, do not let drunken relatives convince you the tenderloin is to rare and should be put back in the oven for a few more minutes. The meat continues to cook after it's out of the oven and you could end up with an expensive yet overdone piece of beef.

Rating: 4
I used canned beef consomme instead of plain beef broth. To save a step, I made a roux with the 3 tbsp. butter and flour with about 4 or 5 tbsp. of fat and pan drippings right in the roasting pan. The sauce came together like velvet after the port/consomme/tomato paste reduction was incorporated and the last 3 tbsp. butter stirred in after it thickened. I crumbled the bacon and added it last. Be not afraid - this was my first beef tenderloin and it was perfection. All of my guests prefer med. rare, so I was concerned when I let the internal temp get over 130 degrees, but after resting 15 minutes, it was just right.

Rating: 4
I highly recommend this recipe! I made this dish for a pre-Christmas dinner and my guests loved it. I only used 1/3 of the roasted shallots and substituted a good Cabernet for the Port but otherwise followed the recipe as written. Using beef tenderloin was costly but it was worth every penny. The sauce itself is superb - one you would find in the finest of restaurants. I will most definitely make this again and again.

